href="gr-004C.xml"
addr="gr-004C"
title="Stabilizer">Stabilizer</fr:link> we see <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a^{-1}b\cdot  x=x]]></fr:tex> and therefore <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\cdot  x=b\cdot  x]]></fr:tex>. Therefore this is a well-defined function.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Reading this argument backwards, we establish <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {f}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="ela-001J.xml"
addr="ela-001J"
title="Injective function">injective</fr:link>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {f}]]></fr:tex> maps <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[gG_{x}]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\cdot  x]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\cdot  x]]></fr:tex> can be an arbitrary element of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G\cdot  x]]></fr:tex>, this means <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {f}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="ela-001I.xml"
addr="ela-001I"
title="Surjective function">surjective</fr:link>. Hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {f}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="ela-001K.xml"
addr="ela-001K"
title="Bijective function">bijective</fr:link>.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
