xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>15466</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">iaa-0003</fr:addr><fr:route>iaa-0003.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Preferatory notes">Preferatory notes</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>14</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="alex-nelson.xml"
addr="alex-nelson"
title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>This is loosely following the material covered in the Math 5 series at <fr:link
type="local"
href="caltech.edu.xml"
addr="caltech.edu"
title="California Institute of Technology">California Institute of Technology</fr:link> (based on Dummit and Foote's <fr:link
type="local"
href="dummit-2004-abstract.xml"
addr="dummit-2004-abstract"
title="Abstract Algebra">Abstract Algebra</fr:link>) or the Math 150 series at <fr:link
type="local"
href="ucdavis.edu.xml"
addr="ucdavis.edu"
title="University of California, Davis">University of California, Davis</fr:link> (based on Artin's <fr:link
type="local"
href="artin-2010-algebra.xml"
addr="artin-2010-algebra"
title="Algebra">Algebra</fr:link>).</fr:p><fr:p>We have already seen a number of different "species" of Mathematical Gadgets, like:</fr:p><fr:ul><fr:li><fr:link
type="local"
href="vectsp-0001.xml"
addr="vectsp-0001"
title="Vector Space">Vector Space</fr:link></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:link
type="local"
href="field-0001.xml"
addr="field-0001"
title="Field">Field</fr:link></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-000K.xml"
addr="ca-000K"
title="Metric Space">Metric Space</fr:link></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:link
type="local"
href="gt-0002.xml"
addr="gt-0002"
title="Topological space">Topological space</fr:link></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:link
type="local"
href="nst-0001.xml"
addr="nst-0001"
title="Set">Set</fr:link></fr:li></fr:ul><fr:p>It turns out, all the information which was really interesting was encoded in the "structure-preserving transformations" between them. (That was the bulk of our time spent studying <fr:link
type="local"
href="ela.xml"
addr="ela"
title="Elementary linear algebra">Elementary linear algebra</fr:link> and <fr:link
type="local"
href="ila.xml"
addr="ila"
title="Intermediate linear algebra">Intermediate linear algebra</fr:link>, after all!)</fr:p><fr:p>We can form an abstraction describing this situation where we have a [gadget] and [transformations] between them: this is category theory.</fr:p><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1564</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">iaa-0005</fr:addr><fr:route>iaa-0005.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Traditional way of teaching abstract algebra">Traditional way of teaching abstract algebra</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="alex-nelson.xml"
addr="alex-nelson"
title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The traditional way we teach undergraduates is by introducing several types of gadgets in abstract algebra in the following order:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>Initially, there's some discussion of set theory sufficient for developing algebra. This is "time honored tradition" starting with van der Waerden's book.</fr:li>
<fr:li>When the structure-preserving transformations leave something invariant (e.g., <fr:link
type="local"
href="vectsp-001P.xml"
addr="vectsp-001P"
title="Invariant subspace">Invariant subspace</fr:link>s in linear algebra), composing such transformations also leaves the thing invariant. This is the guiding intuition of what a "symmetry" is, and the "collection of symmetries" is precisely what a "group" is (originally, they were a "group of symmetries" or a <fr:em>symmetry group</fr:em>).</fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:p>(a) But we also saw how, e.g., square matrices have a neat <fr:link
type="local"
href="ela-000B.xml"
addr="ela-000B"
title="Matrix Algebra">algebraic structure</fr:link> with matrix addition and matrix multiplication. They act like a "number system". This is precisely what is studied with number ring (or just a <fr:link
type="local"
href="ring-0001.xml"
addr="ring-0001"
title="Ring">Ring</fr:link>). A sufficiently nice ring is a <fr:link
type="local"
href="field-0001.xml"
addr="field-0001"
title="Field">Field</fr:link>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>(b) We can generalize linear algebra to describe "vector spaces over arbitrary rings", and these are modules.</fr:p></fr:li>
<fr:li>Galois theory is offered as the pinnacle of abstract algebra, connecting group theory to field theory. Honestly, I never understood the excitement behind Galois theory, since the beautiful parts of it are just the representation theory of groups (describing how "the same symmetries appearing in different situations").</fr:li></fr:ol><fr:p>This is just the first 7 chapters of van der Waerden's <fr:link
type="local"
href="van-der-waerden-1949-modern1.xml"
addr="van-der-waerden-1949-modern1"
title="Modern Algebra, Vol. I">Modern Algebra, Vol. I</fr:link>. Most textbooks have followed this manner of presentation: Dummit and Foote's <fr:link
type="local"
href="dummit-2004-abstract.xml"
addr="dummit-2004-abstract"
title="Abstract Algebra">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> covers this material in the first 14 chapters; Hungerford's <fr:link
type="local"
href="hungerford-1974-algebra.xml"
addr="hungerford-1974-algebra"
title="Algebra">Algebra</fr:link> does this in the first 6 chapters.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
