xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1566</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">iaa-0006</fr:addr><fr:route>iaa-0006.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Modern ways to teach abstract algebra">Modern ways to teach abstract algebra</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="alex-nelson.xml"
addr="alex-nelson"
title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The more modern approaches to teaching abstract algebra incorporates some degree of category theory into the mix.</fr:p><fr:p>Aluffi's <fr:link
type="local"
href="aluffi-2009-algebra.xml"
addr="aluffi-2009-algebra"
title="Algebra: Chapter 0">Algebra: Chapter 0</fr:link> is perhaps the most bold attempt to reorganize abstract algebra around category theory entirely. Instead of ending at Galois theory, Aluffi concludes with homological algebra.</fr:p><fr:p>Some ideas from the traditional approach (like "groups with operators") turn out to be confused and muddled (which should be replaced with groups acting on other groups).</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
   
