type="machine">#356</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-356.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>14</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="alex-nelson.xml"
addr="alex-nelson"
title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
<fr:p>If I had to teach abstract algebra to undergraduates, I am torn between the traditional approaches (starting from van der Waerden's <fr:em>Moderne Algebra</fr:em> onwards) which I just outlined, and more modern adaptations which wrap everything in the framework of category theory. Aluffi's <fr:em>Algebra: Chapter Zero</fr:em> seemingly attempts a happy medium, and I am unhappy with it.</fr:p>
<fr:p>One fortunate aspect to Forester is that I'm not forced to choose one or the other. I can outline the "traditional" presentation of topics, and the "modern" presentation of topics, and allow the reader to pick which manner of presentation they wish to peruse.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
